'''Alfred Arthur Hinchcliffe Denville''' (27 January 1876 – 23 March 1955<ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Ncommons1.htm The House of Commons Constituencies Beginning with 'N']</ref>) was an [[England|English]] actor, theatre impresario and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician.

Denville, an actor by trade, ran one of the UK's leading [[repertory]] companies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.svp.org.uk/04members/obituaries/denville.htm |title=Obituary of Barry Denville |access-date=7 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723162741/http://www.svp.org.uk/04members/obituaries/denville.htm |archive-date=23 July 2008 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1924 Denville founded [[Denville Hall]], a [[retirement home]] for actors in [[Northwood, London]] that is still in operation.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/joan-hirst-647739.html Obituary of Joan Hirst]</ref>

As a politician Denville was elected as the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Newcastle upon Tyne Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle upon Tyne Central seat]] from [[Sir Charles Trevelyan, 3rd Baronet|Sir Charles Trevelyan]] in the [[United Kingdom general election, 1931|1931 general election]] and held the seat until he was defeated in 1945. For a time he was associated with the [[far right]] of the Conservative Party, and during the 1930s was a leading member of the Friends of National Spain, which stressed support for [[Francisco Franco]] and [[anti-communism]].<ref>Peter Barberis, John McHugh, Mike Tyldesley, Encyclopedia of British and Irish Political Organizations, 2002, p. 182</ref> He had also declared himself to be an admirer of [[Benito Mussolini]] although, in keeping with a number of contemporary Tories who admired the southern European fascists, he was critical of [[Adolf Hitler]].<ref>Richard Griffiths, ''Fellow Travellers on the Right'', Oxford University Press, 1983, p. 263</ref>

