The {{nihongo|'''Aoikan'''|葵館}} was a [[movie theater]] located in the [[Tameike]] section of [[Akasaka, Tokyo|Akasaka]] in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. It existed from the mid-1910s as a high-class foreign film theater, featuring [[benshi]] such as [[Musei Tokugawa]]. After the [[1923 Great Kantō earthquake|Great Kanto earthquake]], it re-opened in October 1924 with a brand-new, modern design created by prominent avant-garde artists. Seisaku Yoshikawa was in charge of the architectural design, Yasuji Ogishima did the sculptural reliefs on the front of the building, and [[Tomoyoshi Murayama]] designed the interior decorations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://20thkenchiku.jugem.jp/?eid=217|title=Aoikan|last=Kikuchi|date=January 13, 2010|publisher=Shūzōko ichigōkan|language=Japanese|accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sainet.or.jp/~junkk/mavo/aoi2ogisima.htm|title=Aoikan rerīfu no chōkokuka Ogishima Yasuji|publisher=Bunriha kenchiku hakubutsukan|language=Japanese|accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref> Murayama also did the cover illustrations for the theater's pamphlets in the first few years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gemart.exblog.jp/1200007/|title=Aoikan to Aoi wīkurī|date=March 12, 2006|publisher=Aoyama biyori|language=Japanese|accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref> Film scholars such as Kenji Iwamoto have noted this theater's significance in Japanese cinematic modernism of the 1920s and 1930s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Nihon eiga to modanizumu, 1920-1930|editor=Kenji Iwamoto|publisher=Riburo Pōto|year=1991|isbn=4-8457-0616-4|language=Japanese}}</ref>

