==History==

===Early performers and venues===
What evidence remains of drama in medieval Birmingham suggests that it was largely religious in its basis. The [[Guild of the Holy Cross]] was established in the 14th century to maintain [[Chantry|chantries]] in the parish church of [[St Martin in the Bull Ring]], and is likely to have presented liturgical drama at its guildhall on [[New Street, Birmingham|New Street]].{{sfn|Cunningham|1950|p=9}} The street now known as Carr's Lane in Birmingham City Centre was originally called "God's Cart Lane", after the Holy Cart used for [[Medieval pageant|religious pageantry]] and the presentation of [[morality play]]s and [[Mystery play|miracle plays]].{{sfn|Cunningham|1950|p=9}} [[Wake]]s were established in [[Deritend]] and in [[Handsworth, West Midlands|Handsworth]] in the 15th century where [[booth drama]] would have been presented.{{sfn|Cunningham|1950|pp=9-10}}

The earliest definite records of dramatic performances in the town are of regular seasonal performances by [[strolling players]] in the early 18th century.{{sfn|Cunningham|1950|p=10}} A booth existed by 1715 in "The Hinkleys" – the area bounded by Smallbrook Street and Dudley Street near the site of the current [[Old Rep]] theatre – and a second, described as a "shed of boards", is recorded a few years later in the meadows that would later be developed as Temple Street.{{sfn|Salberg|1980|p=12}} These later developed into the [[Theatre in Smallbrook Street]] and the [[Playhouse in New Street]],{{sfn|Crompton Rhodes|1924|p=5}} but at this early date would have presented plays and performances by travelling actors of indifferent quality, who carried their costumes and scenery with them on their backs and announced their performances by beating a drum.{{sfn|Salberg|1980|p=12}}

A building "something like a stable" in Castle Yard between High Street and Moor Street was used for dramatic performances from 1730.{{sfn|Cunningham|1950|p=11}} The standard of production in this new venue was reflected in the remarks of [[William Hutton (historian)|William Hutton]], writing later in the century: "here the comedian strutted in painted rags, ornamented with tinsel. The audience raised a noisy laugh, half real and half forced, at three-pence a head."<ref>{{Citation|last=Hutton|first=William|year=1795|title=An History of Birmingham|edition=3rd|publication-place=London|publisher=Thomas Pearson|page=196|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VaJbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA194-IA2|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref> Not all of the performances of this era were of such low quality, however: later playbills suggest that [[George Hallam]] had visited Birmingham with a company of actors from London, and that a repertoire of good quality was being presented in the town, by 1730 at the latest.{{sfn|Crompton Rhodes|1924|p=5}}{{sfn|Cunningham|1950|p=10}}

===Georgian theatre===
[[File:Moor-Street-Theatre-1751.jpg|right|upright|thumb|The [[Moor Street Theatre]], marked as the "Play House", on Samuel Bradford's 1751 map of Birmingham]]
It was in the 1740s that Birmingham emerged as the home of a distinctive theatrical tradition, which had become well-established by 1750.{{sfn|Money|1977|p=87}} The town's first permanent theatre was the [[Moor Street Theatre]], which opened in 1740.{{sfn|Price|1988|p=1}} Though not purpose-built, this was a substantial structure with boxes, a pit, a balcony, two galleries, and significant backstage machinery.{{sfn|Cunningham|1950|pp=12-13}} This new venue brought a major increase in the quality of drama presented in the town. It was managed during the 1740s by [[John Ward (actor)|John Ward]], whose background lay not with provincial [[strolling players]] but with [[London]]'s fashionable [[Lincoln's Inn Fields Theatre]] and [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane]], and with the [[Aungier Street Theatre]] in [[Dublin]].{{sfn|Thompson|1999|p=142}} The Moor Street Theatre featured notable cast-members – [[David Garrick]] himself performed at Moor Street in the 1740s{{sfn|Stephens|1964}} – and presented a credible repertoire: the season for 1744 included [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Othello]]'', ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius Caesar]]'' and ''[[The Tempest]]'', [[John Vanbrugh]]'s ''[[The Provok'd Wife]]'', ''[[Fair Rosamund]]'' and ''[[The Biter Bit]]'', [[William Congreve]]'s ''[[Love for Love]]'' and ''[[The Mourning Bride]]'', and [[John Rich]]'s ''[[The Spaniard Outwitted]]''.{{sfn|Cunningham|1950|p=13}} Performances were given in costumes "proper to the play", reflecting the time and culture in which the drama was set, anticipating Garrick's later reforms at Drury Lane in London.{{sfn|Salberg|1980|p=7}}

The most notable development of the 1740s was John Ward's founding of the [[Warwickshire Company of Comedians]] – Birmingham's first indigenous [[theatre company]].  Ward was the manager of the Moor Street Theatre in the 1740s and had established the company by 1744, when it is recorded as playing in [[Stratford-upon-Avon]].{{sfn|Thompson|1999|p=142}}{{sfn|Pendleton|2010|pp=38-39}}{{sfn|Money|1977|p=87}} At a time when any actor outside London was officially "deemed to be a rogue and a vagabond"{{sfn|Price|1973|p=175}} the Birmingham company's performances were of much higher standard than was usual outside London.<ref>{{Citation|last1=Highfill|first1=Philip H.|last2=Burnim|first2=Kalman A.|last3=Langhans|first3=Edward A.|year=1993|contribution=Ward, John 1704-1773, actor, manager, singer|contribution-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TGgS9VxWJ0oC&pg=PA258|title=A Biographical Dictionary of Actors, Actresses, Musicians, Dancers, Managers & Other Stage Personnel in London, 1660-1800|publication-place=Carbondale|publisher=Southern Illinois University Press|volume=15|pages=258–262|isbn=0809318024|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TGgS9VxWJ0oC|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref> A reviewer of their performance in Stratford on Avon in 1746 described them as "much ye best Set I have seen out of London, & in which opinion I am far from being singular"{{sfn|McManaway|1949|p=299}} and the memoirs of the contemporary Irish actor [[Charles Lee Lewes]] speak of "the Great Ward" who "has now a very great company at Birmingham: many of them are no less than Londoners".<ref>{{Citation|last=Lewes|first=Charles Lee|year=1805|title=Memoirs of Charles Lee Lewes: containing anecdotes, historical and biographical, of the English and Scottish stages, during a period of forty years|volume=2|publication-place=London|publisher=Richard Phillips|page=130|oclc=1943377|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=glAOAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA130|accessdate=2014-02-09}} Ward maintained an interest in theatrical affairs in London throughout the 1740s{{sfn|McManaway|1949|p=299}}</ref> Many of the actors in his company had experience from London and Dublin{{sfn|McManaway|1949|p=304}} and the company's repertoire included works by Congreve, Dryden, Lee, Rowe, Shakespeare, Steele, and Vanbrugh, as well as more populist fare including pantomime, music and dance.{{sfn|Thompson|1999|p=142}}

Developments in Birmingham's theatrical culture were not confined just to the new theatre. The [[Playhouse in New Street]] and the [[Theatre in Smallbrook Street]] – successors to booths recorded earlier in the century{{sfn|Cunningham|1950|pp=10-11}} – continued to operate through the 1740s, though both had disappeared by 1751.{{sfn|Stephens|1964}} Serious plays co-existed with more vulgar entertainments at all Birmingham's theatres – from musical concerts to fire-eating, rope-dancing to ventriloquism – often at the same venue, sometimes even on the same evening.{{sfn|Stephens|1964}} Popular dramatic entertainment much like later [[music hall]] was also often held in the town's larger public houses, including the "George and Dragon" and the "Red Lion" in the [[Bull Ring, Birmingham|Bull Ring]], the "King's Head" in [[Digbeth]] and the "Roe Buck" in Cox Street. Though popular these were illegal and often prosecuted by the owners of the more established theatres, who viewed them as unwelcome competition.{{sfn|Cunningham|1950|p=14}}

The [[Licensing Act of 1737]] confined drama in England to the two London [[patent theatre]]s, otherwise forbidding "every Person who shall for Hire, Gain or Reward, act, represent or perform, any Interlude, Tragedy, Comedy, Opera, Play, Farce, or other entertainment of the stage"{{sfn|Price|1973|p=175}} To get round this all Birmingham theatrical venues were licensed by magistrates for the performances of "Concerts of Music" under the [[Disorderly Houses Act 1732]], with plays technically being given free of charge during the interval.{{sfn|Crompton Rhodes|1924|pp=7-8}} Such licenses were only available for 60 day periods between June and October, however, as a result of which Birmingham theatres had only summer seasons until the licensing of the [[Theatre Royal, Birmingham|Theatre Royal]] in 1807.{{sfn|Stephens|1964}}

===Twentieth century theatre===
By 1901 Birmingham had ten theatres.{{sfn|Cochrane|2006|p=91}} The Tivoli (later the [[Birmingham Hippodrome|Hippodrome]]) and the Lyceum (later the [[New Alexandra Theatre|Alexandra Theatre]]) showed melodrama, pantomime, circus and variety acts.{{sfn|Cochrane|2006|p=91}} The [[Theatre Royal, Birmingham|Theatre Royal]] and the [[Prince of Wales Theatre, Birmingham|Prince of Wales]], which had closed their stock companies, received touring modern and classical drama from leading national actor-managers.{{sfn|Cochrane|2006|p=91}}

===Post-war theatre===
The outbreak of the [[Second World War]] saw the enforced closure of all Birmingham's theatres in anticipation of immediate bombing.{{sfn|Salberg|1983|p=123}} Although they were allowed to reopen after a few weeks, the onset of the [[Birmingham Blitz]] in 1940 led to a collapse in attendance at evening performances and the return of closure for the majority of theatres.{{sfn|Salberg|1983|p=123}} The [[Birmingham Repertory Theatre]] was closed for two years from December 1940, and only the [[New Alexandra Theatre|Alexandra Theatre]] would stay open for the entire remaining duration of the war.{{sfn|Salberg|1983|p=123}} The most notable theatrical development of the war years were the [[Plays in the Park]], that saw Birmingham's theatre companies working around the threat of evening bombing of the city centre by presenting matinèe performances of drama in the city's parks.{{sfn|Cochrane|2006|p=91}}

The opening of the [[Sutton Coldfield transmitting station]] in 1949 made Birmingham the first British city outside London to have a [[television]] service, and this came to have a severe effect on the city's commercial theatres.{{sfn|Salberg|1983|p=124}} [[Moss Empires]] closed the [[Theatre Royal, Birmingham|Theatre Royal]] in 1958, with the replacement proposed as part of the [[Alpha Tower|ATV Centre]] never materialising.{{sfn|Salberg|1983|pp=124-125}} The [[New Alexandra Theatre|Alexandra Theatre]] was suffering financial problems by 1956, being forced to seek a loan from [[Birmingham City Council]] in 1963 and from the [[Arts Council]] in 1968.{{sfn|Salberg|1983|pp=131-132}} In October 1968 it was bought by the City Council and leased to a non- profit making management trust.{{sfn|Salberg|1983|p=132}} The Alex's repertory company was closed in 1974 and the company continued as a [[receiving house]].{{sfn|Salberg|1983|p=132}} Moss Empires threatened to close the [[Birmingham Hippodrome|Hippodrome]] in 1961 and 1970, but in 1979 sold it to the City Council who in turn leased it to a [[charitable trust]].{{sfn|Salberg|1983|p=129}} The Hippodrome's fortunes gradually revived, and by the early 21st century it was selling more tickets than any other single theatre in the country.<ref>{{Citation|title=Glenn Howells and Mike Hayes join board of Birmingham Hippodrome|newspaper=Birmingham Post|publisher=Trinity Mirror Midlands|publication-date=2012-04-19|url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/glenn-howells-mike-hayes-join-3913104|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> By the 1980s Birmingham had only three large-scale professional theares, though this was still – jointly with [[Manchester]] – the highest number of any English city outside London.{{sfn|Salberg|1983|p=127}}

During the 70s, mac, then known as the Midlands Arts Centre for Young People had its own professional puppet theatre and resident theatre company, members of the theatre company included Mike Leigh, Brian Blessed and Sir Tony Robinson.

==Contemporary theatre==

===Drama===

====Producing theatres====
[[File:Birmingham-Rep-from-South-East.jpg|thumb|right|[[Birmingham Repertory Theatre]]]]
[[Birmingham Repertory Theatre]], commonly known as "The Rep" and located next to the [[Library of Birmingham]] on [[Centenary Square]], is one of Britain's leading [[producing theatre]]s.<ref name="ArtsCouncil-Rep">{{Citation|year=2013|title=Birmingham Repertory Theatre Company|publication-place=London|publisher=Arts Council England|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/birmingham-repertory-theatre-company/|accessdate=2014-02-09|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204222151/http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/funding/browse-regularly-funded-organisations/npo/birmingham-repertory-theatre-company/|archivedate=2014-02-04|df=}}</ref> It stages a wide range of performances in its three auditoria in Birmingham – ''The House'' with 825 seats, ''The Studio'' with 300 seats and ''The Door'' with 140 seats – as well as touring nationally and internationally and transferring productions to London's [[West End theatre|West End]].<ref name="ArtsCouncil-Rep" /> The Rep regularly commissions new work and presented over 130 new plays during the five-year period to 2013.<ref name="ArtsCouncil-Rep" />

The [[Birmingham Stage Company]] is the resident company at the 383 seat [[Old Rep]] in Station Street, where it performs 5 major productions annually before touring them as far afield as [[Singapore]], [[Dubai]], [[New York City|New York]] and [[Sydney]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Our Top 5 Theatres in Birmingham|newspaper=Birmingham Mail|publication-place=Birmingham|publisher=Trinity Mirror Midlands|publication-date=2013-10-18|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/theatre/top-5-theatres-birmingham-6204911|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref> Founded in 1992, it has focused on new and contemporary plays since 1998, producing world premieres by playwrights including [[Oren Lavie]], [[Paul Lucas (playwright)|Paul Lucas]], [[Dominic Leyton]], [[David Mamet]] and [[Reg Cribb]].<ref>{{Citation|year=2013|title=Birmingham Stage Company|publication-place=Birmingham|publisher=Birmingham Stage Company|url=http://www.birminghamstage.com/userfiles/files/Skellig_Pack_09_8348.pdf|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>

The [[Blue Orange Theatre]] is a small [[fringe theatre]] based in the [[Jewellery Quarter]], with a flexible theatre space seating between 90 and 100 people.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Venue|publication-place=Birmingham|publisher=Blue Orange Theatre|url=http://www.blueorangetheatre.co.uk/thevenue.htm|accessdate=2014-02-09|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910155134/http://www.blueorangetheatre.co.uk/thevenue.htm|archivedate=2011-09-10|df=}}</ref> Although primarily a producing theatre it also hosts visiting companies and runs comedy nights, workshops and courses.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Blue Orange Theatre|publisher=Birmingham fest|oclc=|url=http://birminghamfest.co.uk/locations/blue-orange-theatre/|accessdate=2014-04-22}}</ref>

====Touring venues and companies====
The [[New Alexandra Theatre|Alexandra Theatre]] and the [[Birmingham Hippodrome]] host large-scale touring productions, while professional drama is performed on a wide range of stages across the city, including the [[Old Rep]], the [[Crescent Theatre]], the [[Custard Factory]], the [[Old Joint Stock Theatre]], the [[Blue Orange Theatre]], [[The Drum (Arts Centre)|the Drum]] in [[Aston]] and the ''[[Mac (Birmingham)|mac]]'' in [[Cannon Hill Park]].During the 70s, mac, then known as the Midlands Arts Centre for Young People had its own professional puppet theatre and resident theatre company, members of the theatre company included Mike Leigh, Brian Blessed and Sir Tony Robinson.

Touring [[theatre company|theatre companies]] in Birmingham include the experimental [[Stan's Cafe]], the politically radical [[Banner Theatre]], the [[Birmingham Stage Company]] and the [[Maverick Theatre Company]].

===Dance===
[[File:Birmingham Royal Ballet - E=MC2 - February 2011.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Birmingham Royal Ballet]] performing in [[Tokyo]] in 2011]]
The [[Birmingham Royal Ballet]] is one of the United Kingdom's three major [[Ballet company|ballet companies]] and the only one based outside London.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sanjoy|last=Roy|title=Step-by-step guide to dance: Birmingham Royal Ballet|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2009/apr/08/dance-birmingham-royal-ballet|work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media|date=2009-04-08|accessdate=30 October 2011|quote=See also: The Royal Ballet, English National Ballet – the other two of the big three UK ballet companies.}}</ref> It is resident at the [[Birmingham Hippodrome]] and tours extensively nationally and internationally. The company's associated ballet school – [[Elmhurst School for Dance]] in [[Edgbaston]] – is the oldest vocational dance school in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballettrust.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=15:specialist-dance-schools-up-to-gcse&catid=2:information&Itemid=2|title=Specialist dance schools up to GCSE|accessdate=30 October 2011|publisher=The Ballet Trust|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112112810/http://www.ballettrust.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=15:specialist-dance-schools-up-to-gcse&catid=2:information&Itemid=2|archivedate=12 January 2012|df=}}</ref>

===Opera===
The [[Birmingham Opera Company]] under artistic director [[Graham Vick]] has developed an international reputation for its [[avant-garde]] productions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/rfo/birmingham-opera-company/|title=Birmingham Opera Company|date=25 September 2009|publisher=Arts Council England|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020164933/http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/rfo/birmingham-opera-company/|archivedate=20 October 2011|df=}}</ref> which often take place in factories, abandoned buildings and other [[Stage (theatre)#Created and found spaces|found spaces]] around the city.<ref>{{cite journal|last=O'Neill|first=Sinéad|date=Summer–Autumn 2009|title=Getting out of the House: Unorthodox Performance Spaces in Recent British and Irish Productions|journal=The Opera Quarterly|volume=25|issue=3–4|page=291|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/opera_quarterly/v025/25.3-4.o-neill.pdf|accessdate=14 March 2011|doi=10.1093/oq/kbp045 }}</ref> In 2010 it was described by ''[[The Guardian]]'' as "far and away the most powerful example that I've experienced in this country of how and why opera can still matter."<ref>{{cite news|first=Tom|last=Service|title=Love opera. Don't fall into the trappings trap|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/tomserviceblog/2010/may/27/opera-robert-thicknesse-snobbery|work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media|date=28 May 2010|accessdate=14 March 2011}}</ref> More conventional seasons by [[Welsh National Opera]] and other visiting opera companies take place regularly at the [[Birmingham Hippodrome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/rfo/welsh-national-opera/|title=Welsh National Opera|date=25 September 2009|publisher=Arts Council England|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110919142709/http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/rfo/welsh-national-opera/|archivedate=19 September 2011|df=}}</ref>

