'''''Time and the Wind''''' is a [[musical revue]] by composer [[Galt MacDermot]] and lyricist by [[Norman Matlock]].<ref name="nyt">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/11/theater/theater-review-romantic-adventures-of-3-urban-couples.html|title=Theater Review: Romantic Adventures Of 3 Urban Couples|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 11, 1995|author=[[Stephen Holden]]}}</ref> Directed and choreographed by [[Louis Johnson (director)|Louis Johnson]] with musical direction by MacDermot, the show premiered [[Off-Broadway]] at the John Houseman Studio Theater on July 27, 1995 with costumes by Bernard Johnson and lighting by Deborah Constantine.<ref name="book">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fgOqZWHCLbUC&pg=PA457&dq=%22Galt+MacDermot%22+%22Time+and+the+Wind%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwii89_1rYDYAhXKNiYKHYUZAeoQ6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=%22Galt%20MacDermot%22%20%22Time%20and%20the%20Wind%22&f=false|title=Off Broadway Musicals, 1910–2007: Casts, Credits, Songs, Critical Reception and Performance Data of More Than 1,800 Shows|author=Dan Dietz|page=457|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]}}</ref> The show was produced by Eric Krebs and AMAS Musical Theater Inc.<ref name="nyt"/> It starred [[Christopher Jackson (actor)|Christopher Jackson]], Carol Denise, Russell Joel Brown, Suzanne Griffin, Johnetta Alston, and [[Carl Hall (singer)|Carl Hall]].<ref name="book"/> In his review in ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Stephen Holden]] wrote, "The show calls itself "a New York musical revue," but aside from "Gentle Rain," which compares people to cockroaches, the lyrics include few references to urban life. The predominant musical style is the gospel-flavored pop-soul that flourished 25 years ago but has long since been usurped by funk, rap and hip-hop."<ref name="nyt"/>
==Plot== The show follows the relationship arcs of three unidentified romantic couples: a young streetwise couple, a 30 something yuppy pair, and a middleaged argumentative couple.<ref name="nyt"/>
